<p class="hcp3">Step 3 of 6:</p>
<p class="hcp3">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp4">The default settings 
 in JCAT specify that either cause alone will likely cause Tony to commit 
 murder. &nbsp;However, 
 we can reason that simply having a motive or opportunity alone is not 
 enough for Tony to commit murder. &nbsp;&nbsp;But, 
 if we have both motive AND opportunity, then the probability for murder 
 drastically increases.</p>
<p class="hcp4">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp4"><a title="Click here to read about modeling Probability."
														href="Probabilities.htm"
														id=a2
														target=_blank
														style="font-weight: bold;">To 
 model this</a>, right click on “Commit murder” and return to the Edit 
 Event dialog. &nbsp;Now, 
 select the “Specified Probabilities” tab. &nbsp;You 
 will see the two incoming mechanisms, Motive and Opportunity, displayed 
 in a table. &nbsp;In 
 the column labeled “alone” we can specify what the probability will be 
 that “Commit murder” is caused by either of the mechanisms acting alone. 
 &nbsp;By default, 
 these are set to 0.75, meaning that if Tony has either motive or opportunity 
 by itself, there is a 75% chance he will commit murder. &nbsp;Let’s 
 adjust this.</p>
<p class="hcp4">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp4">First, find the space 
 in the “alone” column associated with Opportunity; let’s set this value 
 to 0.01. &nbsp;This 
 says that if Tony only has an opportunity to commit murder but no motive, 
 there is only a 1% chance he will do so. &nbsp;We 
 can set this value either my directly entering the text, or by adjusting 
 the arrow buttons on the cell.</p>
<p class="hcp4">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp4">Now, Tony might be 
 the kind of character who has a chance of committing murder when he has 
 a motive even if he doesn’t have an opportunity. &nbsp;So, 
 lets set the probability of Motive in the “alone” column at 0.3, meaning 
 Tony has a 30% chance of committing murder with motive alone.</p>
<p class="hcp4">&nbsp;</p>
